english:
  title: On the Deception of Beauty
  author: Lee Gyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There are those in this world seduced by beauty. But what do we mean by beauty? Is it red or white, green or crimson? The sun, moon, and stars, mist and clouds, grass and trees, birds and beasts—all possess color. Can these truly bewitch us? No, they cannot. Then what of the luster of gold and jade, the splendor of fine garments, the grandeur of palaces and pavilions, the delicate weave of brocade and silk? These too embody beauty in its fullest form. Can these deceive us? Perhaps, yet not entirely. For true beauty—the beauty that enchants—is the beauty of human form: dark hair and fair skin, adorned with oils and cosmetics, eyes that meet with invitation, a smile that topples kingdoms. All who gaze upon it are rendered senseless; all who encounter it fall into delusion. In the height of favor and affection, not even brothers and kinsmen compare. Yet this favor becomes rejection, and this affection becomes theft. Have you not heard? The arch of the eye is a blade; the curve of the brow, an axe; the fullness of the cheek, poison; the smoothness of skin, hidden decay. The axe cuts, the blade pierces, the decay eats within, the poison torments. Is this not the cruelest of harms? And when harm becomes enemy, how can we prevail? Thus we call it theft. When we meet a thief, we perish—how can we then reconcile? Thus we call it rejection.

    Yet the inner harm is but the beginning; the outer harm cuts far deeper. Hearing of beauty's allure, men squander their fortunes without hesitation to possess it. Lured by beauty's charms, men rush toward danger as readily as moths to flame. To cherish beauty breeds suspicion among men and envy in the hearts of many. To bear beauty upon oneself brings ruin to honor and name. Whether king or minister, the result is the same: kingdoms fall and houses crumble—none escape this fate. The Precious Consort of Zhou, the beauty of Wu, the Lovely Blossom of the Chen court, the Yang Concubine of Tang—all seduced their sovereigns with honeyed charm, breeding chaos in their wake. Zhou fell because of her; Wu crumbled because of her; Chen and Tang collapsed and perished because of her. In smaller measure, the coy grace of Green Pearl destroyed Stone Chong; the bewitching beauty of Sun Shou seduced the mighty. Such tales are too numerous to count.

    Alas! I would stoke the flames and forge the visage of Matron Mo and the Swarthy One—ten thousand, hundred million copies of their homely faces—and seal within them all such deceptive beauty. Then I would tear out the lustful eyes of beauty's slaves and replace them with eyes of clarity and virtue. I would forge new hearts of honest steel for the greedy and wanton. Then, though they possessed all the fragrant oils and cosmetics in the world, these would become but filth and mud. Though they beheld the grace of Mao Qiang and Xi Shi themselves, they would see only the plain and homely. Then, truly, what beauty could seduce them?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Matron Mo (嫫母) and the Swarthy One (敦洽) were legendary ugly women in Chinese tradition, often cited as the antithesis of beauty.
  - key: ''
    value: Green Pearl and Stone Chong, Yang Precious Consort and Emperor Xuanzong—these are historical or legendary figures whose entanglements with beauty led to disaster and death.
  - key: ''
    value: The repeated invocation of historical examples serves to demonstrate how beauty has repeatedly brought ruin to both rulers and commoners throughout history.
